As you can see, both approaches are neither very extensible nor maintainable, although suitable.

Similarly to EntityFramework, Java provides different ORM that you can use to alleviate these problems.

The first one is [MyBatis](https://mybatis.org/mybatis-3/getting-started.html).

Simplifying a lot, with MyBatis you need a `SqlSession`, an artifact that correctly configured will allow you to obtain a reference to a `Mapper`.

A `Mapper` is just an interface that declares different methods, one per every operation you need to perform against the database. A typical code block will be by like the following:

```java
try (SqlSession session = sqlSessionFactory.openSession()) {
  ProductMapper mapper = session.getMapper(ProductMapper.class);
  //...
}
```

Where:

```java
public interface ProductMapper {
  List&lt;Product&gt; getProducts();
}
```

For every `Mapper` you need to provide an associated [XML configuration file](https://mybatis.org/mybatis-3/sqlmap-xml.html). This file will define as namespace the `Mapper` and, typically, for every method defined in the `Mapper`, the appropriate configuration. For example:

```xml
